1 Future value

Formula \[ FV = P(1+\frac{r}{m})^{nm} \]

Example A company should pay $20 million after 4 years. It can invest money at annual rate of 7% semiannually. How much shoud the company invest today? \[ 20,000,000 = P(1+\frac{7\%}{2})^{2\cdot4} \] Answer

20000000/((1+(0.07/2))^(1/8))

2 Continuous compounding

Since \[\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty } (1+\frac{a}{n})^n = e^a\] we have \[\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty } (1+\frac{r}{m})^n = e^r\] Thus in continuous compounding, the future value should be \[ FV = Pe^{rn}\] # Conversion between compunding method \(r_1\): Annual rate with continuous compunding method \(r_2\): Equivelant rate compounded \(m\) times per annum Since \[ FV = P(1+\frac{r_2}{m})^{mn}=Pe^{r_1 \cdot n} \] We have \[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} r_1 &=m\ln(1+\frac{r_2}{m}) \\ r_2 &= m(e^{\frac{r_1}{m}}-1) \end{aligned} \end{equation} \] Example Consider interest rate of 10% with quarterly compounding. Whats the equivelent rate with continunous rate?

4*log(1+(0.1/4))
[1] 0.09877045

3 Annuity

  • Ordinary annuity: pays out the same amount of money at the end of month.
  • Annuity due: receives the same amount of money at the begining of the month.

3.1 Ordinary annuity

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} FV &= C +C(1+r)+...+C(1+r)^{n-1} \\ &= \sum_{i=0}^{n-1}C(1+r)^{i} \\ &= C \frac{(1+r)^n-1}{r} \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

Allowing compounded \(m\) times:

\[ FV =C \frac{(1+\frac{r}{m})^{nm}-1}{\frac{r}{m}} \]

3.2 Annuity due

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} FV &= C(1+r)+...+C(1+r)^n \\ &= \sum_{i=1}^{n}C(1+r)^{i} \\ &=C(1+r)\frac{(1+r)^n-1}{r} \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

Allowing compounded \(m\) times:

\[ FV =C (1+\frac{r}{m})\frac{(1+\frac{r}{m})^{nm}-1}{\frac{r}{m}} \] ## Present value of the general annuity \[ P=\sum_{i=1}^{mn}C(1+r)^{-i} = C \frac{1-(1+\frac{r}{m}^{-nm})}{\frac{r}{m}} \] Example The \(P\) of an annuity of $100 per annum for 5 yeats at annual rate of 6.25% is

# define annuity function
cal_annuity <- function(c, r, p) {
  a <- 0
  for (i in 1:p) {
    temp <- (1 + r)^(-i)
    a <- a + temp
  }
  return(c * a)
}
# calculate annuity
cal_annuity(100,0.0625,5)
[1] 418.3869

6 Zero-Coupon Bonds

The \(price\) of a zero coupon bonds that pays \(F\) dollars in \(n\) periods follows: \[ Price = \frac{F}{(1+r)^n} \] Example: The interest rate is compounded semiannually. A zero coupon bond that pays the par value 20 years from now will be priced at how much of its par value? \(r=8\%,m=2,n=20\) \[ \frac{Price}{F} = \frac{1}{(1+\frac{r}{m})^{nm}}= \frac{1}{(1+\frac{8\%}{2})^{20\cdot2}} \]

1/((1+(0.08/2))^(20*2))
[1] 0.208289

If the bond matures in 10 years instead of 20 years, the price will be

1/((1+(0.08/2))^(10*2))
[1] 0.4563869

7 Level coupon bond

  • Invester will received coupon each period.
  • Denote par value \(F\), annual counpon rate \(c\) and the coupon received in each period \(C\).
  • The total number of periods is \(n\).
  • Assume the interest compound \(m\) times annualy, the general price formula of the level coupon bond is:

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} P &=\frac{C}{(1+\frac{r}{m})}+...+\frac{C+F}{(1+\frac{r}{m})^n} \\ &= \frac{F}{(1+\frac{r}{m})^n}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}C(1+\frac{r}{m})^{-i} \\ &= \frac{F}{(1+\frac{r}{m})^n} +C\frac{1-(1+\frac{r}{m})^{-n}}{r} \end{aligned} \end{equation} \] where the coupon received at each period \(C\) is given by $ $.

Example 15% BEY, 10 years bond with compound rate of 10% paid semiannually should sell for (Hint: assume the par value is 100)

  • Without loss of generality, let par value \(F=100\).
  • Interest rate \(15\%\), \(m=2\)
  • Total number of periods \(n=2 \times 10 = 20\)
  • Coupon received at each period \(C = \frac{100 \times 0.1}{2}\).
(100*0.1/2)*((1-(1+(0.15/2))^(-10*2))/(0.15/2))+(100/(1+(0.15/2))^(10*2))
[1] 74.51377

Example 15 years, 9% coupon rate

# define yield-price function 
cal_price <- function(n, c, m) {
  p <- c()
  s <- seq(0.075, 0.105, 0.005)
  for (i in 1:length(s)) {
    p[i] <- 100 / ((1 + s[i] / m)^(n * m)) + (100 * c / m) * ((1 - (1 + (s[i] / m))^(-n * m)) / (s[i] / m))
  }
  return(p)
}
# calculate the prices under different yield 
cal_price(15, 0.09, 2)

9 Bond price volatility

Volatility measures how bond price changes wrt change of the interest rate

Sensitivity of the percentage price change wrt to the change of the interest rate: \[ \frac{\frac{\partial{P}}{\partial{y}}}{P} \] ## Duration ### Macaulay duration (MD)

The Macaulay duration (MD) is a weighted average of the times to an assets cash flows.

The weights are cash flows present value divided by the assets price.

\[ \mathrm{MD}\triangleq \frac{1}{P} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{C_{i}}{(1+y)^{i}} \cdot i \]

(Duration)

-

  • Consider the sensitivity of the price of level-coupon bond wrt to the interest rate.
  1. The price of the level-coupon bond is

\[ P = \frac{C_{1}}{1+r} +\frac{C_{2}}{(1+r)^2}+\frac{C_{n}+F}{(1+r)^n} \]

  1. The price change wrt return rate is
$$ \[\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \frac{\mathrm{d}P }{\mathrm{d} (1+r)} &= \frac{\mathrm{d}\left [ C_{1}(1+r)^{-1}+...+(C_{n}+F)(1+r)^{-n} \right ] }{\mathrm{d} (1+r)} \\ &= -C_{1}(1+r)^{-2} + (-2)C_{2}(1+r)^{-3}+...+(-n)(C_{n}+F)(1+r)^{-n-1} \end{aligned} \end{equation}\]

$$

  1. The percentage change in \(P\) and the percentage change in \(1+r\) is

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \frac{\% \Delta \ in \ P}{\% \Delta \ in \ (1+r)} &= \frac{\frac{\mathrm{d}P }{P}}{\frac{\mathrm{d}(1+r) }{1+r}} \\ &= \frac{\mathrm{d} P}{\mathrm{d} (1+r)} \frac{1+r}{P}\\ &= \left [ -C_{1}(1+r)^{-1} + (-2)C_{2}(1+r)^{-2}+...+(-n)(C_{n}+F)(1+r)^{-n}\right ]/P \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

  1. Define MD of the level-coupon bond is

\[ \mathrm{MD}\triangleq \frac{1}{P} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{C_{i}}{(1+y)^{i}} \cdot i + \frac{nF}{(1+r)^{n}} \]

then we have

\[ \frac{\% \Delta \ in \ P}{\% \Delta \ in \ (1+y)} = -\mathrm{MD} \]

9.0.1 Modified duration

1+y(y)(p/p)1%

Since

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \frac{\% \Delta \ in \ P}{\% \Delta \ in \ (1+y)} &= \frac{\mathrm{d} P}{\mathrm{d} (1+y)} \frac{1+y}{P}\\ &= -\mathrm{MD} \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

thus we have

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \frac{\% \Delta \ in \ P}{ \Delta \ in \ (1+y)} &= \frac{\mathrm{d} P}{\mathrm{d} (1+y)} \frac{1}{P}\\ &= -\frac{\mathrm{MD}}{1+y} \\ &\triangleq - \mathrm{Modified \ Duration} \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

Note that if we measure in the annual interest rate, then we have

\[ \frac{\mathrm{MD}}{1+\frac{YTM}{n}} = \mathrm{Modified \ Duration} \]

Thus, the percentage price change is equal to negative Modified Duration multiply the yield change.

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \% \Delta \ in \ P &= - \mathrm{Modified \ Duration} \cdot \Delta \ in \ (1+y) \\ \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

Example: Modified duration 11.54, change in yield 0.1%, the price should decrease 1.154%

12 Forward rate

Consider 2 types of investment:

  1. Invest 1 dollar to \(j\) periods, get \(\left [ 1+S(j) \right ]^{j}\) dollar at time \(j\).

  2. Invest 1 dollar in bonds for \(i\) periods, at time \(i\) invest proceeds in bonds for another \(j-i\) periods, where \(j>i\).

We will have \(\left [ 1+S(i) \right ]^{i} \cdot \left [ 1+S(i,j) \right ]^{j-i}\) dollars at time \(j\).

Define \(S(i,j)\) to be the \((j-i)\) period spot rate \(i\) periods from now, and called it forward rate \(f(i,j)\).

Since the PV of these 2 kinds of investment should be equal, we have

\[ \left [ 1+S(j) \right ]^{j} =\left [ 1+S(i) \right ]^{i} \cdot \left [ 1+S(i,j) \right ]^{j-i} \]

thus we have

\[ S(i,j) = \left \{ \frac{\left [ 1+S(j) \right ]^{j}}{\left [ 1+S(i) \right ]^{i}}\right \}^{\frac{1}{j-i}} -1 \triangleq f(i,j) \]

\[ P = \max (0,X-S) \]

When the stock price is higher than the strike pirce (\(S>X\)), the investor will give up put option.

13.8.2 Formula

$$ \[\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} c &= S_{0}N(d_{1})-Ke^{-rT}N(d_{2}) \\ p &= Ke^{-rT}N(-d_{2})-S_{0}N(-d_{1}) \\ where \ \ d_{1} &= \frac{\ln(S_{0}/K)+(r+\sigma^{2}/2)T}{\sigma \sqrt(T)} \\ d_{2} &= \frac{\ln(S_{0}/K)+(r-\sigma^{2}/2)T}{\sigma \sqrt(T)} = \sigma \sqrt(T) \\ \end{aligned} \end{equation}\]

$$

  • Concept: (\(S_{0}\)) (\(K\))\(\sigma\)()\(r\)

13.8.3 Put Call Parity

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} C+Xe^{-rT} &= P+S \\ where \ \ C &= call \ premium \\ Xe^{-rT} &= present \ value \ of \ the \ strike \\ P &= put \ premium \\ S &= the \ current \ price \ of \ the \ underline \\ \end{aligned} \end{equation} \] * Geometric Bronian Motion

\[ \mathrm{d}S_{t} := \mu S_{t}\mathrm{d}d_{t} +\sigma S_{t} \mathrm{d}B_{t}, 0\leq t \leq T \] where \(S_{t}\) is the stock price at time \(t\), \(\mu\) is the drift rate(),\(\sigma\) is the volatility of the price in years, \(B_{t}\) is the Brownian motion. Notice that \(\mu, \sigma\) are constants.
